    explanation: "**Standardized surgical complication classification + reporting** — essential for quality improvement + research + benchmarking. **Clavien-Dindo Classification** (Dindo D et al, Ann Surg 2004) — universal language for surgical complications, based on therapy intensity required to manage. Validated, simple, widely adopted globally. **Grades I-V** as described. **CCI (Comprehensive Complication Index)** — Slankamenac et al — improvement over reporting most severe complication only; sums all complications weighted by severity (Clavien-Dindo grade × frequency) → 0-100 score. More accurate reflection of complication burden; useful for research comparing groups. **Specific complication definitions** — standardized definitions improve consistency: - **SSI** — CDC NHSN: superficial (within 30 days, involving skin + subQ), deep (≥ 30 days or up to 90 days with implant, involves fascia + muscle), organ/space (deeper) - **Anastomotic leak** — definition varies by anatomy; consensus statements exist for specific procedures (rectal, esophageal, gastric, etc.) - **AKI** — KDIGO: ≥ 0.3 mg/dL Cr increase within 48h OR ≥ 1.5× baseline within 7 days OR UO < 0.5 mL/kg/h × 6h; staging 1-3 - **Sepsis-3** (2016) — life-threatening organ dysfunction from dysregulated host response to infection; SOFA score change ≥ 2 - **Septic shock** — vasopressor needed for MAP ≥ 65 + lactate > 2 despite fluid - **MI (4th universal definition)** — troponin + ischemia evidence (symptoms, ECG, imaging) - **Delirium** — CAM or CAM-ICU **Quality improvement databases**: 1. **ACS NSQIP** — National Surgical Quality Improvement Program — risk-adjusted outcomes; benchmark + feedback; participating hospitals improve over time; > 800 hospitals globally 2. **STS National Database** — cardiothoracic 3. **MBSAQIP** — bariatric 4. **VSGNE** — vascular New England 5. **TQIP** — trauma 6. **NTDB** — National Trauma Data Bank **Research reporting standards** (EQUATOR Network): - **CONSORT** — randomized trials - **STROBE** — observational - **PRISMA** — systematic reviews + meta-analyses - **CARE** — case reports - **STROCSS** — surgical case series - **IDEAL** — surgical innovation - **TRIPOD** — prediction models **Risk adjustment** — important for fair comparison; ASA class, comorbidities, age, urgency adjust for case mix. **Patient-reported outcomes (PROs)** — increasingly emphasized: quality of life, functional outcomes, satisfaction; complement traditional clinical endpoints.",
