    correct_answer: "B",
    explanation: "**Chronic Post-Surgical Pain (CPSP)** — emerging recognition; common (10-50% varies by procedure); under-recognized + under-treated. **Definition** (IASP): pain persisting > 3 months post-surgery, beyond expected healing, not pre-existing, not explained by other cause. **High-risk procedures**: 1. Amputation (phantom limb + stump pain) — 50-80% 2. Thoracotomy — 30-50% 3. Mastectomy — 20-50% 4. Inguinal hernia repair — 10-15% (severe 1-3%) 5. Cardiac surgery (sternotomy) — 20-30% 6. Joint replacement — 10-20% 7. C-section — 10-15% 8. Cholecystectomy — 5-10% **Risk factors**: - Pre-op: pre-existing chronic pain, female, younger age, depression/anxiety/catastrophizing, genetic, opioid use - Surgical: nerve injury, type of incision, surgical experience, surgery duration - Post-op: severity of acute pain, opioid escalation, complications **Mechanisms**: - Peripheral sensitization (inflammation, neuroplasticity at injury site) - Central sensitization (CNS amplification of pain signals; descending inhibition impaired) - Neuropathic (nerve injury — transection, traction, compression, neuroma) **Prevention** (more effective than treatment): 1. Multimodal analgesia (perioperative) 2. Regional anesthesia (continuous nerve blocks, epidural) reduces CPSP in some studies 3. Minimally invasive surgery 4. Nerve preservation + identification (e.g., hernia surgery — identify all 3 nerves) 5. Gabapentinoid perioperative — controversial; recent meta-analyses + RCTs (Verret M et al — meta-analysis suggests less benefit than previously thought) 6. Aggressive acute pain control 7. Identify + address psychological factors pre-op 8. Limit opioid duration post-op 9. Patient education + expectation setting **Assessment**: multidimensional (intensity, function, mood, sleep, social impact). Validated tools: BPI (Brief Pain Inventory), DN4 (neuropathic features), pain catastrophizing scale, PROMIS measures. **Treatment**: multimodal, multidisciplinary: 1. Non-opioid first-line (NSAID, acetaminophen, topicals) 2. Neuropathic-targeted (gabapentin, pregabalin, duloxetine, TCA) — better evidence for some conditions 3. Interventional (blocks, ablation, SCS, intrathecal) 4. Surgical (neurectomy, neuroma excision, mesh removal, hardware removal) — selected 5. Physical therapy + exercise 6. Psychological (CBT, mindfulness, ACT, pain neuroscience education) 7. Lifestyle 8. Opioids: last-line for chronic non-cancer pain; if used, careful — lowest dose, multimodal, functional goals, monitoring, PDMP, screening, naloxone co-prescription. **Opioid epidemic context**: judicious use post-op, limit duration + supply, educate patients, safe disposal, naloxone for at-risk, address opioid use disorder when present (MAT — methadone, buprenorphine, naltrexone). **Multidisciplinary pain clinic** for complex/refractory.",
