    correct_answer: "B",
    explanation: "**Pediatric solid tumors** — distinct from adult cancers in biology, behavior, treatment, outcomes. Childhood cancer overall now > 85% 5-yr survival; substantial late-effect concern. **Major pediatric solid tumors**: 1. **Neuroblastoma** — most common extracranial solid tumor in children; neural crest origin (adrenal, paraspinal sympathetic); median age 18 mo; presentation variable (mass, neuro symptoms, paraneoplastic — opsoclonus-myoclonus). INRGSS staging + risk groups (low/intermediate/high based on age + MYCN + ploidy + histology + others). High-risk treatment: induction chemo → surgery → high-dose chemo + autologous stem cell rescue (sometimes tandem) → RT to primary → maintenance with retinoic acid + anti-GD2 immunotherapy (dinutuximab) — improves survival. Stage MS (infant with skin/liver/marrow involvement) may spontaneously regress in selected. 2. **Wilms tumor** — most common pediatric renal; median 3 yr; SIOP (neoadjuvant chemo before nephrectomy) vs COG (upfront nephrectomy then chemo) — both with > 90% survival favorable histology. Bilateral 5-10% — nephron-sparing emphasis. Anaplastic histology worse prognosis. 3. **Rhabdomyosarcoma (RMS)** — most common pediatric soft tissue sarcoma; embryonal most common (favorable), alveolar worse (PAX3/7-FOXO1 translocation). Sites: head/neck (orbital + parameningeal + non-parameningeal), GU (bladder, prostate, paratesticular, vulva/vagina), extremity, trunk. Multimodal — chemo (VAC backbone) + surgery + RT. 4. **Hepatoblastoma** — most common pediatric liver tumor; AFP marker; PRETEXT staging guides resectability + neoadjuvant chemo + surgery (hepatectomy or transplant if extensive). ~ 80% cure. 5. **Ewing sarcoma** — bone + extraosseous; small round blue cell; EWSR1-FLI1 translocation. Multimodal. 6. **Osteosarcoma** — most common primary bone tumor; adolescent; distal femur most common; neoadjuvant chemo + limb-sparing surgery; ~ 70% cure if localized. 7. **Retinoblastoma** — most common pediatric intraocular; RB1 (Knudson 2-hit); familial (germline — bilateral, multifocal, second cancer risk lifelong) vs sporadic. Intra-arterial chemo emerging; focal therapies preserve vision. 8. **Germ cell tumors** — different biology from adult; sacrococcygeal teratoma classic neonatal. 9. **CNS** — most common pediatric cancer; medulloblastoma + ependymoma + various gliomas + ATRT + craniopharyngioma. Treatment modifications by age + risk. **Pediatric oncology principles**: - Multidisciplinary teams - Risk-adapted therapy - Clinical trial enrollment (high % in pediatric) - Reduce late effects (de-escalate when feasible based on better risk stratification) - Family + child-centered care - Long-term follow-up + survivorship - Specialized pediatric oncology centers (Children's Oncology Group sites). **Tumor biology** distinct: fewer mutations overall, often translocations or copy number changes driving disease; epigenetic + transcription factor-driven. Increasing precision oncology — pediatric MATCH + APEC etc. trials testing molecularly-targeted approaches.",
