    explanation: "**Ovarian mass** — common; differential by age + features. **US characterization (IOTA criteria)** + tumor markers + clinical features guide management. **Algorithm**: 1. **TVUS** — primary imaging 2. **Markers** age-appropriate: - CA-125 — post-menopausal especially - AFP, β-hCG, LDH — young women (germ cell) - HE4, ROMA, RMI — risk algorithms 3. **MRI** — indeterminate cases 4. **CT** — staging if malignancy 5. **Surgical evaluation** — by appropriate surgeon (gynecologist for benign-appearing, gynecologic oncologist for suspected malignancy) **Common ovarian masses by age**: - **Reproductive (15-45)**: functional cysts (follicular, corpus luteum), endometrioma, mature cystic teratoma (dermoid), cystadenoma (serous, mucinous), borderline tumor, germ cell, less commonly epithelial cancer - **Postmenopausal (> 45-50)**: any complex mass concerning for cancer; benign also possible (cystadenoma, fibroma) **Ovarian cancer types**: 1. **Epithelial** (90%): - High-grade serous (most common; often BRCA, TP53; thought to arise from fallopian tube — STIC lesion) - Low-grade serous - Endometrioid - Clear cell - Mucinous (often borderline; if invasive consider GI primary) - Brenner 2. **Germ cell** — young women (teens-30s); dysgerminoma, immature teratoma, yolk sac, choriocarcinoma, mixed; treatable + curable even advanced 3. **Sex cord-stromal** — granulosa cell (estrogen-producing), Sertoli-Leydig (androgen-producing), thecoma, fibroma 4. **Metastatic (Krukenberg)** — from gastric, breast, colon **Surgical management**: - **Benign-appearing premenopausal**: laparoscopic cystectomy (preserve ovary if reproductive-age + benign-appearing) - **Benign-appearing postmenopausal**: laparoscopic oophorectomy ± salpingectomy - **Suspected malignancy**: gynecologic oncologist; staging laparotomy (peritoneal washings + omentectomy + lymph node sampling + biopsies); cytoreductive surgery for advanced (R0 strongest prognostic factor) - **Adnexal torsion**: surgical emergency; detorsion + preservation when feasible; oophoropexy if recurrent **Ovarian cancer treatment**: - Surgery (debulking — R0 cytoreduction = no visible disease — best outcomes) - Adjuvant chemo (carboplatin + paclitaxel) - Maintenance bevacizumab (advanced) - PARP inhibitor maintenance (olaparib, niraparib, rucaparib) — BRCA+, HRD+, or all newly diagnosed advanced (PRIMA, PAOLA-1, SOLO-1 trials) - Recurrence: platinum-sensitive (> 6 mo) vs resistant **Genetics**: BRCA1/2 (10-15% ovarian Ca), Lynch (10%), other genes (PALB2, RAD51 family, ATM); cascade testing of family; risk-reducing salpingo-oophorectomy. **Risk reduction**: oral contraceptives (50% reduction if 5+ yr), tubal ligation, RR salpingo-oophorectomy in BRCA+ at 35-40 (BRCA1) / 40-45 (BRCA2), opportunistic salpingectomy (emerging — STIC theory — fallopian tube origin of high-grade serous).",
