    correct_answer: "B",
    explanation: "**Open fracture management** — orthopedic surgical emergency; principles aim to prevent infection (osteomyelitis) + preserve function. **Gustilo-Anderson classification** — guides management + prognosis: - **I**: < 1 cm, clean, low-energy - **II**: > 1 cm, moderate soft tissue damage - **III**: extensive soft tissue or high-energy; subdivided: - IIIA: adequate soft tissue coverage available - IIIB: bone exposure + flap coverage needed - IIIC: vascular injury requiring repair **Key principles**: 1. **IV antibiotic ASAP** — strongest evidence (within 1 hour, ideally < 3 hr); cefazolin (I-II); cefazolin + aminoglycoside (III) — though newer studies suggest cefazolin alone may suffice in many; tailor to wound + local antibiogram. Penicillin/metronidazole for farm/soil contamination (Clostridium). 2. **Tetanus**: status + booster ± Tig 3. **I&D timing**: classic '6-hour rule' less evidence-based per modern data (FLOW + LEAP + others); within 24h acceptable + may not change outcomes; urgent if severe contamination, vascular compromise, compartment syndrome 4. **Irrigation** — low-pressure NS preferred (FLOW NEJM 2015 — high-pressure no advantage + may push bacteria deeper; antiseptic additives no benefit) 5. **Debridement** — all devitalized tissue + foreign body; assess viability; repeat as needed 6. **Fracture stabilization**: external fixation initially for severe; convert to internal when clean; primary internal in selected (less contaminated, fresh) 7. **Soft tissue coverage**: primary closure if clean + tension-free; otherwise wound VAC + delayed primary closure OR flap (Godina principle — early flap improves outcomes; within 72h ideal in tibial fractures) — local, regional, free flap by reconstructive plastic surgery 8. **Infection surveillance** + treatment **Compartment syndrome** — major concern: - 6 P's: pain disproportionate, pallor, paresthesia, paralysis, pulselessness (late), poikilothermia - Pain with passive stretch most sensitive - Compartment pressures > 30 mmHg or within 30 of diastolic = positive - Fasciotomy emergent **Mangled extremity** + decisions about salvage vs amputation: - **MESS score** + clinical judgment - LEAP study — long-term functional outcomes similar for salvage vs amputation in selected severe lower extremity injuries - Patient + multidisciplinary input - Quality of life considerations **Vascular injury** (IIIC) — vascular repair priority; shunt for distal perfusion while orthopedic stabilization, then definitive bypass. **Long-term outcomes**: pain, function, return to work, psychological all important; rehabilitation + multidisciplinary; chronic osteomyelitis significant risk despite optimal management; PTSD common in major extremity injury patients (especially combat-related).",
