    correct_answer: "B",
    explanation: "**Walled-off Pancreatic Necrosis (WOPN)** — late complication of necrotizing pancreatitis; encapsulated collection of necrosis + fluid; typically forms by 4+ weeks. **Distinction from acute necrotic collection (ANC, < 4 weeks)** + pseudocyst (no solid necrotic content) + acute peripancreatic fluid collection (APFC). Atlanta 2012 classification. **Management paradigm shift** — from early aggressive open necrosectomy (high mortality ~ 30-50%) → delayed step-up approach (lower mortality ~ 5-20% modern series). **PANTER trial (van Santvoort et al, NEJM 2010)** — landmark: - Step-up: PCD → MIS necrosectomy as needed - Open: traditional approach - Results: step-up reduced new-onset multi-organ failure + complications (without mortality difference; subsequent updates suggest mortality benefit); set standard for management **TENSION trial (van Brunschot et al, Lancet 2018)** — endoscopic step-up vs surgical step-up: - Endoscopic step-up (LAMS cystgastrostomy + DEN) reduced new organ failure (vs surgical step-up) - Similar mortality - Less pancreatic fistulas - Less ICU stay - Endoscopic approach growing in centers with expertise **Step-up approach steps**: 1. **Wait** for walled-off (4+ weeks) unless infected + decompensating 2. **Percutaneous drainage** first — IR-guided; retroperitoneal route preferred (left flank — avoids peritoneal contamination + creates sinus tract for later interventions) 3. **Antibiotic** if infected (carbapenem — meropenem, imipenem — penetrate pancreatic tissue well; fluoroquinolone alternative) 4. **Minimally invasive necrosectomy** if percutaneous inadequate at 4-7 days: - VARD (video-assisted retroperitoneal debridement) - Endoscopic transgastric (LAMS cystgastrostomy + DEN) - Laparoscopic transgastric - Sinus tract endoscopy 5. **Open necrosectomy** — last resort; rare in modern centers **Indications for intervention**: 1. Infected necrosis (clinical, gas on CT, positive FNA) 2. Persistent symptoms (pain, GOO, failure to progress) 3. Complications (bleeding pseudoaneurysm — IR embolization first; mass effect) Sterile necrosis usually NOT intervened — better with supportive. **Bleeding pseudoaneurysm** — major mortality contributor in pancreatitis: visceral aneurysm in inflamed area; IR angio + embolization first-line; surgery if failed. **Long-term sequelae**: - Pancreatic exocrine insufficiency — PERT - Pancreatic endocrine (type 3c DM) - Pseudocyst (residual) - Chronic pancreatitis - Strictures (biliary, GI) - Pancreatic cancer slightly elevated risk - Quality of life impact substantial.",
