    explanation: "**Long-term complex multimorbid patient management** — challenging but central to modern medicine + surgery. Most adults have multiple chronic conditions; care should be integrated + patient-centered. **Key principles**: 1. **Patient-centered**: 'What matters to you?' (Berwick + others) — alongside 'What's the matter with you?' — frames care around patient goals + values 2. **Multimorbidity-focused** vs disease-by-disease — recognize interactions, prioritize, balance, individualize 3. **Geriatric principles**: comprehensive geriatric assessment (CGA), functional + cognitive emphasis, polypharmacy deprescribing, falls prevention, social context 4. **Care coordination**: primary care medical home, care manager, multidisciplinary teams, shared EHR, transitions of care protocols 5. **Patient + family engagement**: education, self-management, shared decision-making 6. **Health equity**: address social determinants (housing, food security, transportation, employment, social support), language access, health literacy, cultural humility 7. **Advance care planning** — ongoing, not single event; revisit with health changes; healthcare proxy, advance directive, POLST/MOLST 8. **Palliative care integration** — concurrent with disease-modifying treatment; not just end-of-life; symptom management + quality of life + family support 9. **Caregiver support** — major modifiable factor; burden assessment, respite, education, mental health, community resources **Specific tools + approaches**: - **5 Ms of geriatric care**: Mind, Mobility, Medications, Multicomplexity, what Matters most - **Comprehensive Geriatric Assessment** - **Deprescribing protocols** (STOPP/START, Beers) - **POLST / MOLST** — actionable medical orders, portable across settings, complement advance directive - **Healthcare proxy designation** **Models of care**: - **Patient-Centered Medical Home (PCMH)** - **Accountable Care Organizations (ACO)** - **PACE (Program of All-Inclusive Care for the Elderly)** — frail elderly in community - **Hospice + palliative care** - **Chronic care management programs** **End-of-life care** — comfort, dignity, symptom management, family support, hospice when appropriate, bereavement support extending 12+ months. **Quality measurement**: patient experience (HCAHPS), patient-reported outcomes (PROMs), functional outcomes, advance care planning completion, caregiver burden, healthcare utilization. **Equity** — recognize disparities; provide language access, health literacy-appropriate education, address SDoH, cultural humility, advocate for policy changes. **Workforce**: interdisciplinary training, primary care + geriatrics + palliative care; nursing, social work, pharmacy, physical/occupational therapy, mental health all critical; team-based care.",
